values.description: The ball bearing was escaping the `round_tin_*` meshes. It seemed that the ball_bearing model was only generating contact when it hit one of the edges of the trimesh; it seemed to pass directly through triangles. I wasn't able to figure out what caused the problem. Instead I increased the density of the meshes. I also simplified the meshes so that they have a plain cylinder on the bottom and the meshes are just the walls of the tins. The inertia doesn't account for the base of the tins yet either...

This is my contribution to gazebo_models, for adding moon surface model:

* height map is taken from http://wms.lroc.asu.edu/lroc/view_rdr_product/NAC_DTM_APOLLO15_E261N0036
* As for visual texture map, I cropped image from http://www.hq.nasa.gov/alsj/a17/AS17-134-20508HR.jpg, but if someone knows better data, let me know
* As for depth(height) scaling, I could not find any data, so I just manually adjust them, just to look better.
* http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=dem, nasa site provides us .TIF or .IMG, and I'm not sure on relationship between DEM and IMG

values.description:
This pull request adds 3 submarine models: `buoyant_submarine`, which has a density of 500 kg/m^3, `submarine`, which has a density of 1000 kg/m^3, and `sinking_submarine`, which has a density of 1500 kg/m^3.

These models are used to test the `BuoyancyPlugin`: in water, which has a density of 1000 kg/m^3, we would expect the `buoyant_submarine` to float upwards, the `submarine` to maintain equilibrium, and the `sinking_submarine` to sink.

Besides their respective masses and colors, the submarines are identical. Each features a 4-blade propeller with a 20 degree pitch. The `LiftDragPlugin` enables the `submarine` model to slowly propel itself forward when a force or velocity is applied to the `spinning_joint` (I recommend the left menu for this).

[gazebo PR for BuoyancyPlugin](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/pull-request/1622/buoyancyplugin-for-fluid-dynamics)
values.title: Added submarines of varying density

This pull request adds 3 submarine models: buoyant_submarine, which has a density of 500 kg/m^3, submarine, which has a density of 1000 kg/m^3, and sinking_submarine, which has a density of 1500 kg/m^3.

These models are used to test the BuoyancyPlugin: in water, which has a density of 1000 kg/m^3, we would expect the buoyant_submarine to float upwards, the submarine to maintain equilibrium, and the sinking_submarine to sink.

Besides their respective masses and colors, the submarines are identical. Each features a 4-blade propeller with a 20 degree pitch. The LiftDragPlugin enables the submarine model to slowly propel itself forward when a force or velocity is applied to the spinning_joint (I recommend the left menu for this).
